            "body": "@guilherme-batalheiro, I'm not entirely sure how it works but I'll try my best to explain my understanding. Taking a look at the help pages for the events in the autocmd:\r\n\r\n```\r\nBufHidden\r\nBefore a buffer becomes hidden: when there are\r\nno longer windows that show the buffer, but\r\nthe buffer is not unloaded or deleted.\r\n\r\nNot used for \":qa\" or \":q\" when exiting Vim.\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nBufUnload\r\nBefore unloading a buffer, when the text in\r\nthe buffer is going to be freed.\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nQuitPre\r\nWhen using :quit, :wq or :qall, before\r\ndeciding whether it closes the current window\r\nor quits Vim.  For :wq the buffer is written\r\nbefore QuitPre is triggered.  Can be used to\r\nclose any non-essential window if the current\r\nwindow is the last ordinary window.\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhen ```BufHidden``` is triggered, nvim checks if any associated autocmd made the current buffer the only window. This happens here because we close all open tree windows and the bug only happens if the tree window(s) and the source window are the only open windows. Because of that, E855 is thrown.\r\n\r\n```c\r\n// buffer.c: 596\r\nif (abort_if_last && one_window(win)) {\r\n    // Autocommands made this the only window.\r\n    emsg(_(e_auabort));\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhen doing ```:q```, there is no such check and ```QuitPre``` is called quite early:\r\n```c\r\n// ex_docmd.c: 4748\r\n// Trigger QuitPre and maybe ExitPre\r\nif (before_quit_autocmds(wp, false, eap->forceit)) {\r\n    return;\r\n}\r\n                                                                                                                                          \r\n// If there is only one relevant window we will exit. \r\nif (check_more(false, eap->forceit) == OK && only_one_window()) { \r\n    exiting = true;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI hope this makes it more clear :)\r\n\r\nI'm realizing now that my fix for the original bug introduces another bug:\r\nWhen the source buffer is open multiple times (e.g. when split) and you quit one of these windows, it will also close the tree view which shouldn't happen (that's probably why the code didn't use QuitPre to begin with). The easiest fix would probably be to check if there are multiple source windows open like so:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\napi.nvim_create_autocmd({ 'BufHidden', 'BufUnload', 'QuitPre' }, {\r\n    group = group,\r\n    buffer = buf,\r\n    -- remove this line because E855 would happen again\r\n    -- once = true, \r\n    callback = function()\r\n      -- don't close inpector window if source buffer\r\n      -- has more than one open window\r\n      if #vim.fn.win_findbuf(buf) > 1 then\r\n          return\r\n      end\r\n\r\n      -- close all tree windows\r\n      for _, window in pairs(vim.fn.win_findbuf(b)) do\r\n        close_win(window)\r\n      end\r\n    end,\r\n  })\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'll open an issue (for the sake of completeness) and a pr with the above fix. But maybe there might be a more elegant way to work around this?",
